<DOC><DOCNO> AP880406-0076 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 0720EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     04-06 0346</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0363</SECOND><HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Falls</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The dollar stayed mostly higher in quiet Europeantrading this morning after a brief early rally lost momentum.   Gold prices fell as the dollar appeared to hold on to recentgains, but dealers said they didn't expect the precious metal tofall much further.   Traders in Rome said any movement in the dollar this week islikely to be limited, slow and hesitant because no major economicnews is expected.   ``People are still bearish, but there is fear that the UnitedStates is tightening monetary policy in order to control inflation,and this has created some uncertainty,'' one Italian trader said.   He added that this uncertainty is likely to persist until theApril 14 announcement of the U.S. trade figures for February.   Dealers in Frankfurt cited few fundamental reasons for thedollar's recovery. One cited higher U.S. interest rates and anothersaid the dollar received some support Tuesday from U.S. FederalReserve sales of Britain's pound.   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, thedollar rose 0.60 yen to a closing 125.03. Later, in London, it wasquoted slightly higher at 125.055 yen.   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday'srates:   _1.6692 West German marks, up from 1.6690   _1.3770 Swiss francs, up from 1.3765   _5.6575 French francs, down from 5.6605   _1.8735 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8700   _1,237.50 Italian lire, up from 1,234.50   _1.2390 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2395   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost$1.8780 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.8800 late Tuesday.   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $452.30 a troy ounce. Atmidmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed arecommended price of $450.80, down from Tuesday's late bid of$451.50.   In Zurich, the bid price was $451.10, down from $453.50 lateTuesday.   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold dropped $5.60 to close at a bid$453.21.   Silver also fell in London today. It was selling at a bid priceof $6.59 a troy ounce, down from Tuesday's $6.65.</TEXT></DOC>